body: How about remove "extract_constant_to_initializer" from the passes list?

@doo5643, I think you can use tools to remove those unused initializers. If your graph does not have subgraph, you can try the following:
```
from onnxruntime.transformers.onnx_model import OnnxModel
import onnx
model = onnx.load("input.onnx")
onnx_model = OnnxModel(model)
onnx_model.prune_graph()
onnx_model.save_model_to_file("output.onnx")
```

> How about remove "extract_constant_to_initializer" from the passes list?

@doo5643, please try the following instead (prune_graph could remove nodes, and initializers can be removed by update_graph()):
```
from onnxruntime.transformers.onnx_model import OnnxModel
import onnx
model = onnx.load("input.onnx")
onnx_model = OnnxModel(model)
onnx_model.update_graph()
onnx_model.save_model_to_file("output.onnx")
```

Please try

```
import onnxruntime as ort
so = ort.SessionOptions()
so.optimized_model_filepath = 'output.onnx'
# [optional] so.graph_optimization_level = ort.GraphOptimizationLevel.<your desired optimization level>
ort.InferenceSession('input.onnx',  sess_options=so)
```
The optimized ONNX model (with unused initializers removed) will be saved as `output.onnx`
Note, if you use optimization level `ORT_ENABLE_EXTENDED` or `ORT_ENABLE_ALL`, the optimized model may contain Microsoft contrib operators, and probably can only be executed using ONNX Runtime.

> Please try
> 
> ```
> import onnxruntime as ort
> so = ort.SessionOptions()
> so.optimized_model_filepath = 'output.onnx'
> # [optional] so.graph_optimization_level = ort.GraphOptimizationLevel.<your desired optimization level>
> ort.InferenceSession('input.onnx',  sess_options=so)

@gwang-msft Thank you. Your solution worked well. Now the messages do not show up.
By the way, during optimization, I saw this message showing up. What does this exactly mean?

`2021-10-06 08:51:53.0162759 [W:onnxruntime:, inference_session.cc:1303 onnxruntime::InferenceSession::Initialize] Serializing optimized model with Graph Optimization level greater than ORT_ENABLE_EXTENDED and the NchwcTransformer enabled. The generated model may contain hardware specific optimizations, and should only be used in the same environment the model was optimized in.`

See, https://onnxruntime.ai/docs/performance/graph-optimizations.html
If you use `ORT_ENABLE_ALL`, the optimized model may be platform specific, and it should only be used on the same type of hardware platform where the optimization is performed, for example, if a model is optimized on x86 platform, it may not run properly on arm platform.

> See, https://onnxruntime.ai/docs/performance/graph-optimizations.html If you use `ORT_ENABLE_ALL`, the optimized model may be platform specific, and it should only be used on the same type of hardware platform where the optimization is performed, for example, if a model is optimized on x86 platform, it may not run properly on arm platform.

> @gwang-msft Thank you so much. If I use `ORT_ENABLE_BASIC` , is there no risk that the onnx model will become platform dependent?

Yes, the model optimized by using `ORT_ENABLE_BASIC` is not platform and execution provider dependent.
